British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd arrived  Sunday in the northwestern city of Murmansk at the start of a three-day visit  to Russia and Ukraine.
He was received by his Russian counterpart Andrei Kozyrev, who was elected  as a deputy from Murmansk in last December's legislative elections in Russia.
The two were to hold talks Sunday on NATO's Partnership for Peace program  of military cooperation, ties between the European Union and Russia and the  war in Bosnia-Hercegovina.
On Tuesday Hurd heads to Moscow for talks with President Boris Yeltsin and  Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin.
He is to spend Wednesday in Ukraine, where he will meet President Leonid  Kravchuk.
